{"id":"1708.08855","submitter":"Emmanuel Giroux","authors":"Emmanuel Giroux","title":"Ideal Liouville Domains - a cool gadget","comments":"22 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.SG math.DG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Liouville domains have become central objects in symplectic and contact\ngeometry. However, the auxiliary data they involve --- namely, Liouville forms\n--- and the non-compactness of their completions generate some inconvenience.\nThe notion of ideal Liouville domains is designed to suppress these awkward\naspects and to let symplectic structures play the leading role. Ideal Liouville\ndomains are compact manifolds with boundary whose interior carries a symplectic\nform satisfying some tameness condition along the boundary. Their definition\nand their basic properties are presented in the first part of these notes,\nwhile the second part discusses their relevance in contact geometry.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 29 Aug 2017 16:08:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-08-30"}
