{"id":"1708.08939","submitter":"Alexander Mustill","authors":"Alexander J Mustill, Melvyn B Davies and Anders Johansen","title":"The dynamical evolution of transiting planetary systems including a\n  realistic collision prescription","comments":"Accepted to MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/sty1273","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Planet-planet collisions are a common outcome of instability in systems of\ntransiting planets close to the star, as well as occurring during in-situ\nformation of such planets from embryos. Previous N-body studies of instability\namongst transiting planets have assumed that collisions result in perfect\nmerging. Here, we explore the effects of implementing a more realistic\ncollision prescription on the outcomes of instability and in-situ formation at\norbital radii of a few tenths of an au. There is a strong effect on the outcome\nof the growth of planetary embryos, so long as the debris thrown off in\ncollisions is rapidly removed from the system (which happens by collisional\nprocessing to dust, and then removal by radiation forces) and embryos are small\n($< 0.1\\mathrm{\\,M}_\\oplus$). If this is the case, then systems form fewer\ndetectable ($\\gtrsim1\\mathrm{\\,M}_\\oplus$) planets than systems evolved under\nthe assumption of perfect merging in collisions. This provides some\ncontribution to the \"Kepler Dichotomy\": the observed over-abundance of\nsingle-planet systems. The effects of changing the collision prescription on\nunstable mature systems of super-Earths are less pronounced. Perfect mergers\nonly account for a minority of collision outcomes in such systems, but most\ncollisions resulting in mass loss are grazing impacts in which only a few per\ncent. of mass is lost. As a result, there is little impact on the final masses\nand multiplicities of the systems after instability when compared to systems\nevolved under the assumption that collisions always result in perfect merging.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 29 Aug 2017 18:01:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 14 May 2018 09:16:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-05-23"}
